THE RISK:
{
 "id": "statista-stage-blend-tambase",
 "title": "If Statista's country MW blends pipeline stages, the CE apportionment inside tamBase is counting halls that don't exist yet",
 "narrative": "tamBase's only CE-specific hop is 'CE-7 = 39.8% of Europe colo MW (Statista).' But the corpus shows Statista-style country figures may not be operational-only: summed Statista country colo exceeds CBRE's total European capacity, and the same digest shows how easily vendors blend stages — DC Byte's Amsterdam 'supply' is 1,849 MW while operational capacity is 852 MW, a 2.2x gap. If the Statista series leans toward committed/under-construction capacity, the CE share and the country weights are computed on MW that generate zero PDU revenue in 2026 — and with EMEA construction plateaued at 2.5 GW, much of that phantom base stays phantom through the venture's window. This is a different failure than the ±40% band contemplates: the band prices scope-down uncertainty on the global number, not stage-blending in the one CE-specific multiplier.",
 "category": "fact",
 "targetNodes": [
  "tamBase"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "Vendor capacity figures demonstrably blend pipeline stages: DC Byte reports Amsterdam 'Total Supply' of 1,849 MW (live + under construction + committed + early stage) against 852 MW operational (C&W) — the same city, a 2.2x gap purely from stage definition",
   "refs": [
    "digest:geo-NL#c6",
    "digest:geo-NL#c0"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "tamBase multiplies the €775M Europe estimate by 'CE-7 = 39.8% of Europe colo MW' from the Statista series, whose scope ('colocation and scale-colocation IT power') no second vendor replicates; if it includes non-operational MW, the euro-revenue-relevant CE base is smaller — and with EMEA under-construction plateaued at ~2.5 GW, blended-in pipeline MW does not convert to PDU-buying halls inside 12 months",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:tamBase",
    "digest:geo-NL#c3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The 2025/26 revenue-relevant tamBase sits below the curated €320M for a reason orthogonal to the global-number spread the sensitivity band was built from; every downstream node inherits the overstatement proportionally",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:tamBase",
    "digest:tam-global-crosscheck#c0"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The 240–520 band looks generous, so 'TAM might be smaller' feels handled. But the band's low end was derived from the GLOBAL number's publisher spread; nobody stress-tested the single CE-specific hop — the Statista MW apportionment — for stage-blending, because two capacity 'methods' appeared to triangulate it. Both methods share the same untested scope definition.",
 "expectedObviousness": "low",
 "falsifier": "Statista methodology documentation (or direct reconciliation) confirming the 'colocation and scale-colocation IT power' series counts operational MW only, matching C&W/CBRE operational figures within ~10% for DE and NL.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.25,
  "rationale": "The Amsterdam 852 vs 951 MW and Germany 1,737 vs multiple divergent totals suggest partial rather than gross blending; the >2x DC Byte-style inflation is possible but the Statista figures sit closer to operational anchors than to full-pipeline ones. [evidence revision: The trigger is confirmed (DC Byte definitively blends stages), but the falsifier-relevant evidence pulls against the specific claim about the Statista series: Statista's 2024/2025 country figures (NL 915/951, DE 1,458/1,737) explicitly separate actuals from asterisked forecasts, sit far below DC Byte's blended 1,849 MW, and are broadly consistent with CBRE's operational anchors (Amsterdam >500 MW; European colo supply 4,726 MW). This supports the hypothesis's own likelihood note that Statista leans toward operational anchors, nudging the estimate down slightly from 0.30. Partial blending in outer forecast years remains possible, so the risk is not eliminated.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.3
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "tamBase",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 250,
   "note": "CE apportionment recomputed on operational-only MW; lands near the band's low edge for a cause outside the band's logic"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Per-country operational vs pipeline MW splits for CE-7",
   "where": "Cushman & Wakefield EMEA Data Centre Update (semi-annual, country tables)",
   "threshold": "Statista country figure exceeding C&W operational figure by >20% for DE or NL",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "DC Byte live vs total-supply ratios for Frankfurt, Amsterdam, Warsaw",
   "where": "DC Byte market pages / quarterly market summaries",
   "threshold": "Live share of total supply <55% in the CE hubs",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Commission the IndexBox EU Rack PDUs report (country tables) to anchor the CE base in directly-scoped revenue rather than MW apportionment",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "tamBase",
   "note": "Already the ledger's named promotion path; it removes the Statista hop entirely"
  },
  {
   "action": "Rebuild the CE apportionment using one consistent operational-only source (C&W or CBRE country tables) across all seven countries",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "tamBase",
   "note": "Cheap desk exercise that isolates how much of the 39.8% is stage-blend artifact"
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "contested",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "Amsterdam | DC Byte",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "DC Byte",
   "date": "2025-01-19",
   "excerpt": "Supply: 1,849 MW. Total Supply is the sum of four supply categories: Live, Under Construction, Committed, and Early Stage.",
   "url": "https://www.dcbyte.com/market/amsterdam/",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Europe: Colocation data center power by country 2031",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Statista",
   "date": "2026-02-06",
   "excerpt": "Colocation and scale colocation data center IT power supply in Europe from 2024 to 2031, by country: Netherlands 915 (2024), 951 (2025), 1,086 (2026*); Germany 1,458 (2024), 1,737 (2025). Forecast years marked with asterisk.",
   "url": "https://www.statista.com/statistics/1659712/europe-colocation-data-center-power-by-country/",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Europe Data Centres Figures Q4 2024",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "CBRE",
   "date": "2025-02",
   "excerpt": "4,726MW European colocation supply 470MW European colocation availability 341MW European colocation take-up",
   "url": "https://assoimmobiliare-be.afterpixel.com/app/uploads/2025/02/Europe-Data-Centres-Figures-Q4-2024.pdf",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
